ng, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1111–1162":"about 1111–1162","1111–1162":"1111–1162","1137–1188":"1137–1188","1147–1171":"1147–1171","1095–Female":"1095–Deceased","1137":"1137","1147":"1147","1188":"1188","1111":"1111","1162":"1162","1095":"1095","about 1111":"about 1111","1171":"1171","Hingham, Norfolk, England":"Hingham, Norfolk, England","Hockering, Norfolk, England":"Hockering, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Rea  .","English: topographic name for someone living at a place where rye (Old English <i>ryge</i>) was grown, or perhaps an occupational name for someone who grew or sold it.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, most of them from Old Norse <i>rjóthr</i> ‘clearing in a forest’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ryer","meanings":["English (Sussex and Kent): probably from   Rye   (see   Rea  ) + the suffix <i>-er</i>, and is thus synonymous with Middle English <i>atte Rye</i>, denoting someone who lived by a river or an island. This type of formation is common in Sussex and Kent.","Americanized form of German   Reier   ‘heron’ or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname.","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Rajar</b> or <b>Rajer</b> (see   Rayer  )."]},{"name":"Romney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Romney (Kent), from an uncertain first element (perhaps an Old English personal name <i>Rūmen</i>) + Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river, stream’. Compare   Rye   2."]},{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry 